<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1725,1983]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,322,1802,1828]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described from caves in Iowa and Minnesota (
<bibRefCitation author="Christiansen" box="[1113,1341,1802,1828]" pageId="13" pageNumber="17" refString="Christiansen, K. (1966) The genus Arrhopalites (Collembola: Sminthuridae) in the United States and Canada. International Journal of Speleology, 2, 43 - 73." type="journal article" year="1966">
Christiansen 
<number box="[1276,1341,1802,1828]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1966.0">1966</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), so the occurrence in Arkansas is intriguing. Although P. 
<taxonomicName box="[754,834,1841,1866]" class="Entognatha" family="Arrhopalitidae" genus="Pygmarrhopalites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dubius">
<emphasis box="[754,834,1841,1866]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">dubius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may only be a geographic variant of 
<taxonomicName box="[1286,1435,1841,1866]" class="Entognatha" family="Arrhopalitidae" genus="Pygmarrhopalites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaeus">
<emphasis box="[1286,1435,1841,1866]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">P. pygmaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Christiansen" box="[159,390,1880,1906]" pageId="13" pageNumber="17" refString="Christiansen, K. (1966) The genus Arrhopalites (Collembola: Sminthuridae) in the United States and Canada. International Journal of Speleology, 2, 43 - 73." type="journal article" year="1966">
Christiansen 
<number box="[325,390,1880,1906]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1966.0">1966</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Christiansen" box="[403,789,1880,1906]" pageId="13" pageNumber="17" refString="Christiansen, K. &amp; Bellinger, P. (1998) The Collembola of North America, north of the Rio Grande. A taxonomic analysis. Grinnell College, Grinnell, Iowa, 1520 pp." type="book" year="1998">
Christiansen &amp; Bellinger 
<number box="[723,789,1880,1906]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1998.0">1998</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), there is sufficient morphological differentiation to designate them as a separate species. Additionally, they were collected from the same cave, Forest Trail Ridge Cave, which provides support for a separate status of the species.
</paragraph>
